<p id="4pf7zg"><strong>Where to play: </strong>Nintendo Switch, PlayStation 4, PlayStation 5, Windows PC, Xbox One, Xbox Series X</p>
<p id="qTR388"></p>
<p id="1708539506.803349"><a href="https://www.polygon.com/24033589/prince-of-persia-the-lost-crown-review-ubisoft-switch"><em>Prince of Persia: The Lost Crown</em></a> is so good at what it does, we might need a new name for “Metroidvania.” A Persiavania? A Metroid…prince…ia? Look, the wordsmiths can quibble over the exact phrasing, but the point remains: It’s a rare sight to witness a game instantly establish itself as totemic. </p>
<p id="Nlf1JH"><em>The Lost Crown</em> is initially just a competent platformer, where you navigate a byzantine maze-like palace with routes that unfold as you improve. Then the meticulousness of its assembly dawns on you. Utterly devoid of bloat, not a single pixel out of place, <em>The Lost Crown</em> isn’t just one of the best games of the year — it’s one of the best of the generation. —<em>Ari Notis</em></p>
